		<span class="Tags">
			<b>09 Sep 2010</b>
			 &mdash; <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100914063926/http://www.eu-russiacentre.org/tag/lithuania" rel="tag">Lithuania</a>					</span>
		<p>Here is published an article on the worsening Lithuanian Polish relationship. Warsaw’s ostentatious disappointment with Vilnius’ decision not to support the Russo-Polish initiative to lift the visa regime for the residents of Kaliningrad region may mark the beginning of a freeze in the relations between Lithuania and Poland.<span id="more-16700"></span><br/>
Russia still does not have an accurate list of the Kaliningrad region dwellers. The Lithuanians convinced that this is a matter of the national security. One of the core concerns for Vilnius during negotiations in 2002 for the EU membership was to achieve that the EU would not grant a preferential visa treatment for any other third country, that is Russia and for Kaliningrad. The EU Commission has warned Lithuania and Poland from the trilateral negations and agreements. Especially, having in mind that Lithuania and Poland are unhappy about the French and German similar practices. The Kaliningrad visa facilitation problem has been created by Warsaw intentionally in order to highlight the fact to the Russians and the Polish public that there the strategic relation between Lithuania and Poland has ended.<br/>
It is probably no accident that at the same time when the Polish foreign minister in Kaliningrad was making promises to the Russians, Lithuanian Prime Minister Andrius Kubilius together with the cabinet’s ministers was riding on a bike through Belarus. They were welcomed like representatives of the best friend and ally of Belarus.</p>
<span class="Source">Source: <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100914063926/http://www.lithuaniatribune.com/2010/09/08/lithuania-poland-strategic-partnership-turning-into-strategic-freeze/" target="_blank">The Lithuania Tribune</a></span>	
